Data Sources: https://www.lendingclub.com/info/download-data.action
Download 2015 Loan Data from the “Download Loan Data” section and load the data from csv file into R data frame, and check the dimension of the data:

library(plyr)
library(ggplot2)
setwd("~/data")
data<-read.csv("LoanStats3d.csv",header=TRUE,sep=",")
dim(data)
## [1] 421095    111

Set A

1. Review the dataset and summarize your thoughts on any structural issues:
a. Is there missing data? Is the missing data random or structured: Are some attributes missing more than others?
sum(is.na(data))
## [1] 7963782

There are total 7963782 missing data.

missingdata<-sapply(data, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
ggplot(NULL,aes(x=seq(1,ncol(data)),y=missingdata))+geom_point(col='white')+theme_dark()+xlab("Variables")+ylab("Number of Missing data")

From the scatter plot we can conclude that the missing data is structured, which means the number of missing values are skewed and occur in specific variables.

First, I would inspect those variables which have more than 380,000 missing data:

names(data)[missingdata>380000]
##  [1] "annual_inc_joint"   "dti_joint"          "open_acc_6m"       
##  [4] "open_il_6m"         "open_il_12m"        "open_il_24m"       
##  [7] "mths_since_rcnt_il" "total_bal_il"       "il_util"           
## [10] "open_rv_12m"        "open_rv_24m"        "max_bal_bc"        
## [13] "all_util"           "inq_fi"             "total_cu_tl"       
## [16] "inq_last_12m"
# Plot two variables for sample
ggplot(NULL,aes(x=seq(1,nrow(data)),y=as.numeric(is.na(data$annual_inc_joint))))+geom_point(col='white')+theme_dark()+xlab("Index")+ylab("is.missing(annual_inc_joint)")

ggplot(NULL,aes(x=seq(1,nrow(data)),y=as.numeric(is.na(data$dti_join))))+geom_point(col='white')+theme_dark()+xlab("Index")+ylab("is.missing(dti_join)")

By plotting the scatter plot with observations’ index and missing status, we discovered that most of the missing data is located at the rear of the dataset. In other words, it means that before a specific row, our observation doesn’t have these variables. Also, these variables appears to be missing simultaneously. This kind of situation usually happens due to intentional reasons, e.g.system management issue, business issue.

Then, I will inspect those variables which have more than 150,000 but not more than 380,000 missing data:

names(data)[missingdata<380000 & missingdata>150000]
## [1] "mths_since_last_delinq"         "mths_since_last_record"        
## [3] "mths_since_last_major_derog"    "mths_since_recent_bc_dlq"      
## [5] "mths_since_recent_revol_delinq"
# Plot two variables for sample
ggplot(NULL,aes(x=seq(1,nrow(data)),y=as.numeric(is.na(data$mths_since_last_delinq))))+geom_point(col='white')+theme_dark()+xlab("Index")+ylab("is.missing(mths_since_last_delinq)")

ggplot(NULL,aes(x=seq(1,nrow(data)),y=as.numeric(is.na(data$mths_since_last_record))))+geom_point(col='white')+theme_dark()+xlab("Index")+ylab("is.missing(mths_since_last_record)")

By plotting the scatter plot with observations’ id and missing status, we discover that the missing data seems to be randomly generated without patterns. To discover the reason which caused missingdata, I will recommend discussing with a domain expert or make a thorough analysis between these variables and others. Make sure to figure out the reason that caused the missing data and make a suitable decision to handle this data, e.g. delete it, replace by a fix values, impute it by model or impute it by means, etc.

b. Are any data values glaringly erroneous?

Generally, I will check if there are any glaringly erroneous data by screening data with following features: (1) Out-of-range values (2) Unconsistant data (3) Duplicate or redundant cases: No (4) Empty cases (5) Missing value (6) Outliers

5. Select one of the below topics and explain it to:

linear regression

a. Someone with significant mathematical experience, and

The linear regression model is used to detect and explain the relationship between one dependent variable from another or more independent variables. The dependent variables should be continuous and independent variables can be continuous or categorical. It is often used for explanatory analysis and prediction. The major goal of linear regression is to fit a line through a multi-dimensional cloud of data points with the formula of:

Y=B0+B1X1+B2X2+…+BnXn

Y is the dependent variable and Xi is independent variables, the slopes of independent variables’ individual straight-line relationships with dependent variable are the constants B1, B2, …, Bk. The coefficents imply the change in Y per unit of change in Xi. B0 is the intercept, which implies the value of Y when every xi = 0. The coefficients have been estimated by minimizing the least squares error of the outcome.

There are four major assumptions that have to be satisfied before using linear regression:
(1) The mean of the response variable is linear related to the predictors.
(2) The error terms(residual) are normally distributed.
(3) The error terms(residual) have equal variances.
(4) The error terms(residual) are independent at each preditor value.

Usually, we use the p-value of each predictors to evaluate the significance of relation from Xi to Y, and a smaller p-value implies a strong significant relationship. To evaluate the Goodness-of-fit, we usually use R-square index, which is the square of the correlation between the observed Y values and the predicted values. The higher the R-square is, a more powerful fit the model has.

b. Someone with little mathematical experience. You can use graphics/diagrams if you wish.

The basic principle of linear regression is that we have to find a line or a hyperplan which can best describe the relationship betweeen Xi and Y. For example, in an image we have two variables, X and Y, and there is a linear relation beween them. We can demonstrate this by using installment and loan_amount variables in LC data:

set.seed(1)
p<-sample(nrow(data),200)
datademo<-data[p,]
g<-ggplot(datademo,aes(x=loan_amnt,y=installment))+geom_point(col="5")+theme_dark()
g

Our goal is to try to find a line in a 2-dimensional space which can best fit the linear relation between X and Y as follows:

g+geom_smooth(method="lm",col="7")

“Find the line” means we have to define the coefficent of the line, which means B0 and B1 in the line’s function:

Y=B0+B1X1

Let’s see the coefficent in this case:

fit<-lm(installment~loan_amnt,data=datademo)
summary(fit)
##

## loan_amnt       0.03       0.00   38.84     0.00

In this case the B0 = 34.21, B1 = 0.03, which means the polynomial function of the line is:

Y=34.21+0.03*X

If we got a new X, which is 1, then we can predict that the Y will be 34.24 based on the model.
